review_blob: 2008 vintage poured in a snifter at Austin Flying Saucer. One finger head, nice lacing. Dark brown body. Smell and taste is fruity, sweet and alcoholic in roughly that order. A nice beer, but maybe a little too sweet.
beer_name: Gouden Carolus Cuvee Van De Keizer Blauw/Blue

review_blob: Served in a wine glass at Austin Flying Saucer. One finger off-white head over golden body. Hops dominate smell and taste with a hint of grapefruit up front. Very highly carbonated. The high alcohol is masked well. Fantastic IPA!
Served in a shaker at Austin Flying Saucer. One finger head over golden body. Not much aroma. A sweet caramel hint to the aftertaste. Medium carbonation.
Served in a shaker at Austin Flying Saucer. No head. Ruby body. Not much aroma. Malt pushes hops a little too far into the background for an IPA.

Served in a snifter at Austin Flying Saucer. Three finger off-white head over clean reddish golden body. Citrus hoppy aroma. High alcohol is completely masked by Cascade hops. Medium carbonation. Fantastic!
Served in a shaker at the Austin Flying Saucer. Pours clear gold with one finger head. Smoky aroma over floral hops. Nice carbonation and a crisp aftertaste. An unusual and very drinkable IPA.
Served in a snifter at the Austin Flying Saucer. A one finger head evaporates quickly over an amber body. The alcohol stands in the fore.

Served in a weizen glass at the Austin Flying Saucer (happy hour). A good looking beer with 2 finger head and nearly burgundy body. The rye malt overpowers the hops on the nose and tongue. The alcohol was masked very well.
beer_name: Bear Republic Hop Rod Rye Ale

review_blob: Served in a weizen glass at the Austin Flying Saucer (happy hour). I didnt see it poured, but it came to me headless. There was an orange tint to the color and aroma. Not enough hops for my taste. A very forgettable IPA.

Served in a shaker (from bottle) at Austin Flying Saucer. No remarkable aroma. Pours golden with one finger/one minute head. The malt overpowers the hops: I re-read the label... Carbonation is very light. Overall, a thoroughly unremarkable beer and a questionable IPA.

Served in a snifter at the Austin Flying Saucer. Mahogany body, golden around the edges, 1 finger off-white head lasts about a minute. Strong grapefruit smell and initial taste, enough carbonation to excite the tongue and back of the throat. Citrus/hops and alcohol battle for dominance throughout.  Overall, a must try!
beer_name: Avery The Maharaja Imperial India Pale Ale
